Part 1: Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM)¶

A Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) is a parametric probability density function represented as a weighted sum of KK Gaussian densities. GMMs are commonly used as a parametric model of the probability distribution of a dataset X={x1,…,xM}X={x1,…,xM} where xi∈RNxi∈RN. They are popular due to their capability of representing multi-modal sample distributions. The probability density function (pdf) of a KK-component GMM is of the form,

p(x|Θ)=K∑k=1αkp(x|μk,Σk)(1)(1)p(x|Θ)=∑k=1Kαkp(x|μk,Σk)

where p(x|μk,Σk)p(x|μk,Σk) is the multivariate Gaussian pdf with mean μkμk and covariance ΣkΣk

p(x|μk,Σk)=1(2π)N/2|Σk|1/2exp{−12(x−μk)T(Σk)−1(x−μk)}.(2)(2)p(x|μk,Σk)=1(2π)N/2|Σk|1/2exp⁡{−12(x−μk)T(Σk)−1(x−μk)}.

Θ={θ1,…,θk}Θ={θ1,…,θk} is the complete set of parameters θk={αk,μk,Σk}θk={αk,μk,Σk}, where αkαk are the priors (or mixing weights) of each Gaussian component, which satisfy the constraint ∑Kk=1αk=1∑k=1Kαk=1.

GMMs are widely used in many areas of engineering, due to their modeling structure and flexibility they can be used for clustering, classification and regression purposes (we will cover these applications in TP5-GMM-Applications). The parameters ΘΘ can be estimated from training data using either a Maximum Likelihood parameter estimation approach through the iterative Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm or using Maximum A Posterior (MAP) estimation.

In this assignment, we will implement the EM-algorithm for GMM parameter learning, following the steps covered in the Continuous Distributions slides 48-49 from the Applied Machine Learning course. For the derivation of the EM steps, refer to annexes provided in the course EM Annexes.

Maximum Likelihood (ML) Parameter Estimation for GMMs¶

The aim of ML estimation is to find the model parameters ΘΘ which maximize the likelihood of the GMM given the training dataset XX. For a dataset of MM training data points, the GMM likelihood L(Θ|X)=p(X|Θ)L(Θ|X)=p(X|Θ), assuming the data points are i.i.d (identically and independently distributed) is,

p(X|Θ)=M∏i=1p(xi|Θ)=M∏i=1K∑k=1αkp(xi|μk,Σk).(3)(3)p(X|Θ)=∏i=1Mp(xi|Θ)=∏i=1M∑k=1Kαkp(xi|μk,Σk).

Unfortunately, this equation is a non-linear function of the parameters ΘΘ and direct maximization is impossible. However, an ML estimate can be obtained iteratively using a special case of the expectation-maximization (EM) algorithm which tries to find the optimum of the likelihood, which is equivalent to finding the optimum of the loglog likelihood

maxΘlogL(Θ|X)=maxΘlogp(X|Θ)(4)(4)maxΘlog⁡L(Θ|X)=maxΘlog⁡p(X|Θ)

through the following steps:

  • Initialization step: Initialize priors α={α1,…,αK}α={α1,…,αK}, means μ={μ1,…,μK}μ={μ1,…,μK} and Covariance matrices Σ={Σ1,…,ΣK}Σ={Σ1,…,ΣK}.
  • Expectation Step: For each Gaussian k∈{1,…,K}k∈{1,…,K}, compute the probability that it is responsible for each point xixi in the dataset.
  • Maximization Step: Re-estimate the priors α={α1,…,αK}α={α1,…,αK}, means μ={μ1,…,μK}μ={μ1,…,μK} and Covariance matrices Σ={Σ1,…,ΣK}Σ={Σ1,…,ΣK}
  • Go back to step 2 and repeat until the logL(Θ|X)log⁡L(Θ|X) stabilizes.

  • gmmLogLik.m: The log likelihood of the parameters ΘΘ of a learnt GMM for the given dataset XX

Type of Covariance Matrices¶

Apart from the number of clusters KK, another flexible design decision in GMMs is the type of Covariance matrix ΣΣ to use for each Gaussian component. Three types of ΣΣ can be used:

Full Covariance matrix:¶

The full Covariance matrix is computed as follows:

Σfull=1M−1XXT,(6)(6)Σfull=1M−1XXT,

where XX is the zero-mean data (X→X−¯XX→X−X¯), where ¯XX¯ is the mean of the data. For a 2D dataset the form of ΣΣ is:

Σfull=[σ2xσxσyσyσxσ2y ],Σ∈Rx+y.(7)(7)Σfull=[σx2σxσyσyσxσy2 ],Σ∈Rx+y.

Diagonal Covariance matrix:¶

A diagonal Covariance matrix of a dataset only considers the variance in the principal directions; i.e. disregarding the off-diagonal elements. For a 2D dataset it should have the following form:

Σdiag=[σ2x00σ2y ],Σ∈Rx+y(8)(8)Σdiag=[σx200σy2 ],Σ∈Rx+y

This can be computed from full covariance matrix and extracting only the diagonal values.

Isotropic Covariance matrix:¶

Otherwise known as the circular Covariance matrix is solely dependent on the squared distance |x−x′|2|x−x′|2 between the original points (i.e. non-zero mean) and their mean μμ. Hence, one must compute the isotropic variance as follows:

σ2iso=1NMM∑i=1||xi−¯x||2.(9)(9)σiso2=1NM∑i=1M||xi−x¯||2.

Then replicate it in a diagonal matrix, to have the following form: Σiso=[σ2iso00σ2iso ],Σ∈Rx+y.(10)(10)Σiso=[σiso200σiso2 ],Σ∈Rx+y.

Expectation-Maximization for Estimating GMM Parameters¶

Step 1. Initialize Priors α(0)α(0), Centroids μ(0)μ(0) and Covariance Matrices Σ(0)Σ(0)¶

The EM algorithm for GMM begins with an initialization step. Here we shall initialize for iteration t=0t=0 the following:

  • The set of priors α(0)={α(0)1,…,α(0)K}α(0)={α1(0),…,αK(0)} to uniform probabilities; i.e. α(0)1=⋯=α(0)K=1Kα1(0)=⋯=αK(0)=1K
  • The means μ(0)={μ1(0),…,μK(0)}μ(0)={μ1(0),…,μK(0)} shall be initialized with the KK-Means algorithm.
  • Given the means μ(0)μ(0) and labels computed from the previous step, one can initialize the set of corresponding Covariance matrices Σ(0)={Σ1(0),…,ΣK(0)}Σ(0)={Σ1(0),…,ΣK(0)} choosing the datapoints assigned to each μk(0)μk(0) and using your compute_covariance function.

Step 2. Expectation Step: Membership probabilities¶

At each iteration tt, estimate, for each Gaussian kk, the probability that this Gaussian is responsible for generating each point of the dataset. The a posteriori probability for a kk-th component is given by

p(k|xi,Θ(t))=α(t)kp(xi|μk,Σk)∑Kj=1α(t)jp(xi|μj(t),Σj(t)).(11)(11)p(k|xi,Θ(t))=αk(t)p(xi|μk,Σk)∑j=1Kαj(t)p(xi|μj(t),Σj(t)).

These probabilities are the output of the expectation Step. They must be computed for each k∈{1,…,K}k∈{1,…,K} for all data points i∈{1,…,M}i∈{1,…,M}.

TASK 5.1: Implement expectation_step.m function (2pts)¶

The function has the follosing signature:

In [ ]:
function [Pk_x] = expectation_step(X, Priors, Mu, Sigma, params)

It takes as input XX, the current priors α={α1,…,αK}α={α1,…,αK}, centroids μ={μ1,…,μK}μ={μ1,…,μK}, and covariance matrices Σ={Σ1,…,ΣK}Σ={Σ1,…,ΣK}, and the hyper-parameter structure params. It outputs the posterior probability p(k|xi,Θ(t))p(k|xi,Θ(t)) of each Gaussian kk.

Step 3. Maximization Step: Update Priors αα, Means μμ and Covariances ΣΣ¶

In order to maximize the log-likelihood of the current estimate we update the priors α(t+1)={α(t+1)1,…,α(t+1)K}α(t+1)={α1(t+1),…,αK(t+1)} with the following equation:

α(t+1)k=1MM∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t))(12)(12)αk(t+1)=1M∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t))

The means are updated by the following equation:

μk(t+1)=M∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t))xiM∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t)).(13)(13)μk(t+1)=∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t))xi∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t)).

Finally, the Covariance matrices for each kk-th component are computed with the following equation:

Σk(t+1)=M∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t))(xi−μk(t+1))(xi−μk(t+1))TM∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t)).(14)(14)Σk(t+1)=∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t))(xi−μk(t+1))(xi−μk(t+1))T∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t)).

For full Covariance matrices the previous equation can be used directly to update the Σ(t+1)Σ(t+1). For diagonal Covariance matrices, you can compute the full version and then simply extract the diagonal elements. Now, for isotropic matrices, one must use the following update equation:

Σk(t+1)iso=M∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t))||xi−μk(t+1)||2NM∑i=1p(k|xi,Θ(t)).(15)(15)Σisok(t+1)=∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t))||xi−μk(t+1)||2N∑i=1Mp(k|xi,Θ(t)).

Every so often, during EM iterations, certain Covariance matrices can become ill-conditioned, i.e. the matrix tends to be a singular matrix. In the likelihood sense, this means that the likelihood is converging towards infinity. This happens for various reasons; namely (i) there might be more parameters than datapoints or (ii) the variables are highly correlated. Hence, after estimating the ΣΣ's we must add a tiny variance to avoid this numerical instability, this can be done by adding a very very small number ϵ=1e−5ϵ=1e−5 to the diagonal values of each ΣkΣk .

Part 2: Fitting Gaussian Mixture Models¶

From the GMM equations, one can observe that the set of model parameters are {K,(αk,μk,Σk)Kk=1}{K,(αk,μk,Σk)k=1K}. As in k-means, we can use the AIC and BIC metrics for model selection. To recall:

  • AIC: The AIC metric is a maximum-likelihood measure that penalizes for model complexity as follows:
AIC=−2lnL+2B(16)(16)AIC=−2ln⁡L+2B

where LL the likelihood of the model and BB the total number of model parameters.

  • BIC: The BIC metric goes even further and penalizes for number of datapoints as well with the following equation as follows:
BIC=−2lnL+ln(M)B(17)(17)BIC=−2ln⁡L+ln⁡(M)B

where MM is the total number of datapoints.

For GMMs the computation of the total model parameters BB is more involved than k-means. For a dataset with x∈RNx∈RN, the total number of parameters to learn for a KK-component GMM with full Covariance matrix is:

Bfull=K×(1+2N+12N×(N−1))−1(18)(18)Bfull=K×(1+2N+12N×(N−1))−1

with −1−1 corresponding to the priors constraint ∑Kk=1αk=1∑k=1Kαk=1. For the case of diagonal Covariance matrices,

Bdiag=K×(1+N+N)−1(19)(19)Bdiag=K×(1+N+N)−1

and for isotropic Covariance matrices the number of parameters is computed as follows:

Biso=K×(1+N+1)−1(20)(20)Biso=K×(1+N+1)−1

Choosing the optimal KK¶

For choosing the optimal KK that best describes our dataset with a GMM, we follow the same procedure as in k-means. We estimate the GMM parameters for a range of KK values, 10 times each. For each KK we select the best run, which in likelihood terms, means the run with the maximum likelihood; in other words, we choose the minimum AIC/BIC value from the 10 runs. We then plot the values and select the KK which yields the best tradeoff between likelihood and model complexity.
